library(ggplot2)

top_terms %>%
  mutate(term = reorder(term, beta)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(term, beta, fill = factor(topic))) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~ topic, scales = "free") +
  coord_flip()

The top frequent words are relating to “friend”, “family”, “birthday”, “job”, “dinner”, “husband”, “daughter”,etc. These words showed the core source of happiniess for these people and it reflects what they value the most in their lives. Most of their happiness are relating to friends, Thus, friends play an indispensible role throughout people’s lives no matther what ages they are in, no matter what gender they are, and no matter if they are single or married. Then, I want know as people are getting old, how will their source of happiness change. I will look at top frequent words for people in different ages.

Other than the top frequent words all people are talking about, teenagers also talk about “game”,“event”, “girlfriend”, “finished”, “college”, “exam” frenquently. As for people in 20s, they talk more about “family”, “home”, “job”, “night”. For people in 30s, “friend”, “family” are still top frequent words. Other than that, “son”, “daughter”, “wife”, “husband” become top frequent words. For people in 40s, their top frequent words are similar to those of people in 30s. For people who are older than 50, their top frequent words are still relating to family and friends, which are “friend”, “daughter”, “husband”, “son”, “home”, “wife”.And there are some new words appeared in the list, which are “visit”, “dog”, “love”. As we can see from these top frequent words list, some words are relating to each other. For example, “exam” will be associated with “school” in our common sense.
